    solution:
      "The Black-Scholes call price is\n\n$$C = S_0 N(d_1) - K e^{-rT} N(d_2),$$\n\nwith\n\n$$d_1 = \\frac{\\ln(S_0/K) + (r + \\tfrac{1}{2}\\sigma^2)T}{\\sigma\\sqrt{T}}, \\qquad d_2 = d_1 - \\sigma\\sqrt{T}.$$\n\nSince $S_0 = K$, $\\ln(S_0/K) = 0$. The drift term is $r + \\tfrac12 \\sigma^2 = 0.05 + 0.02 = 0.07$, and $\\sigma\\sqrt{T} = 0.2$. Thus\n\n$$d_1 = \\frac{0 + 0.07 \\times 1}{0.2} = 0.35, \\qquad d_2 = 0.35 - 0.2 = 0.15.$$\n\nUsing the given values $N(d_1) = 0.6368$, $N(d_2) = 0.5596$, and $e^{-rT} = e^{-0.05} \\approx 0.951229$:\n\n$$C = 100 \\times 0.6368 - 100 \\times 0.951229 \\times 0.5596.$$\n\nThe second term is $100 \\times 0.951229 \\times 0.5596 \\approx 95.1229 \\times 0.5596 \\approx 53.231$, so\n\n$$C \\approx 63.68 - 53.231 = 10.449.$$\n\n$$\\boxed{C \\approx 10.45}$$",
